The '''Tesla Model Y''' is a [[battery electric vehicle|battery electric]] [[Compact crossover SUV|compact crossover]] manufactured by [[Tesla, Inc.]] Unveiled in March 2019,<ref name="electrek-2019-03-14">
{{Cite web|url=https://electrek.co/2019/03/14/tesla-model-y-electric-suv-unveil/
|title=Tesla unveils Model Y electric SUV with 300 miles range and 7-seats|last=Lambert|first=Fred
|date=March 15, 2019|website=[[Electrek]]|language=en-US|access-date=March 15, 2019
|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190315055454/https://electrek.co/2019/03/14/tesla-model-y-electric-suv-unveil/|archive-date=March 15, 2019|url-status=live}}
</ref> it started production at its [[Tesla Factory|Fremont plant]] in January 2020,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.caranddriver.com/news/a30705862/tesla-production-results-q4-model-y/
|title=Tesla Beats Expectations, Declares a Profit, and Has Started Model Y Production |last=Baldwin |first=Roberto
|date=January 29, 2020| website=Car and Driver |publisher=Hearst |language=en-US |access-date=February 27, 2020 }}
</ref> and started deliveries on March 13, 2020.<ref name=":0" />

The Model Y is based on the [[Tesla Model 3|Model 3]] sedan platform.<ref name="Mashable-2016-01-29">{{cite news |url=https://mashable.com/2016/01/28/tesla-model-3-variants/|title=Tesla is working on multiple variations of the Model 3|author=Nick Jaynes|date=January 29, 2016|access-date=March 15, 2019|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190330205323/https://mashable.com/2016/01/28/tesla-model-3-variants/|archive-date=March 30, 2019|publisher=[[Mashable]]}}</ref> It shares an estimated 75 percent of its parts with the Tesla Model 3,<ref>{{Cite web|last=Lambert|first=Fred|date=April 8, 2020|title=Tesla Model Y teardown: shows some great improvements over Model 3 despite sharing 75% of parts|url=https://electrek.co/2020/04/08/tesla-model-y-teardown-improvements-over-model-3-sharing-parts/|access-date=October 28, 2020|website=Electrek|language=en-US}}</ref> which includes a similar interior and exterior design and electric powertrain. The Model Y fills a smaller and less expensive segment than the mid-sized [[Tesla Model X]].<ref name="electrek-2017-08-02">{{cite news|author=Fred Lambert|date=August 2, 2017|title=Tesla Model Y is coming to market sooner using Model 3 architecture, says Elon Musk|publisher=electrek|url=https://electrek.co/2017/08/02/tesla-model-y-coming-sooner/|url-status=live|access-date=March 15, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190330205317/https://electrek.co/2017/08/02/tesla-model-y-coming-sooner/|archive-date=March 30, 2019}}</ref> Like the Model X, the Model Y offers optional third-row seats for a seven-passenger seating capacity.<ref name="MotorTrend-2019-03-15">{{cite magazine |author=Miguel Cortina |date=March 15, 2019 |title=Tesla Model Y First Ride: A Compact Crossover For Canyon Roads |url=https://www.motortrend.com/news/tesla-model-y-first-ride/ |url-status=live |magazine=Motor Trend |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190320084459/https://www.motortrend.com/news/tesla-model-y-first-ride/ |archive-date=March 20, 2019 |access-date=March 15, 2019}}
</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Lambert |first=Fred |date=December 2, 2019 |title=Tesla Model Y: rare glimpse at third-row seats |url=https://electrek.co/2019/12/02/tesla-model-y-third-row-seats/ |access-date=February 27, 2020 |website=Electrek |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite tweet|number=1201513627292966913|user=Model3Owners|title=I took better pictures of the third row seats... sheesh|author=Online Tesla Owners|date=December 2, 2019|access-date=December 4, 2019|language=en}}</ref> 

There were four planned powertrain configurations for the Model Y: Standard Range Rear-Wheel Drive (RWD), Long Range Rear-Wheel Drive, Long Range with Dual Motor All-Wheel Drive (AWD), and Performance (with Dual Motor All-Wheel Drive).<ref>{{Cite web|title=Tesla Press Information|url=https://www.tesla.com/presskit|access-date=November 10, 2020|website=Tesla}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|title=2021 Tesla Model Y: Preview, Pricing, Release Date|url=https://www.carsdirect.com/2021/tesla/model-y|access-date=November 11, 2020|website=CarsDirect}}</ref> The Long Range AWD model and the Performance model are currently being delivered.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.tesla.com/modely/design|title=Design Your Model Y {{!}} Tesla|website=www.tesla.com|language=en|access-date=March 27, 2020}}</ref> The Standard Range RWD configuration was initially canceled in July 2020, due to the range ({{cvt|230|mi|km|disp=or}} EPA) being unacceptably low to CEO [[Elon Musk]], but was orderable as of January 2021 (with {{cvt|244|mi|km|disp=or}} of EPA range).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://insideevs.com/news/433680/tesla-cancel-standard-range-tesla-model-y/|title=Tesla Cancels Sub $40,000 Standard Range Tesla Model Y a{{!}} InsideEvs|website=www.insideevs.com|language=en|access-date=July 14, 2020}}</ref><ref name=":1">{{Cite web|last=Hoffman|first=Connor|date=January 8, 2021|title=Tesla Model Y Adds Standard Range Model and Third-Row Option|url=https://www.caranddriver.com/news/a35162425/2021-tesla-model-y-standard-range-announced/|access-date=January 8, 2021|website=Car and Driver|language=en-US}}</ref> By February 7, 2021, the Long Range RWD appears to have been canceled.<ref name=":2">{{Cite web|last=Gurskiy|first=Denis|date=February 3, 2021|title=It Looks Like Tesla Has Canceled the Long Range RWD Model Y|url=https://evbite.com/it-looks-like-tesla-has-canceled-the-long-range-rwd-model-y/|access-date=February 3, 2021|website=EVBite|language=en-US}}</ref> As of December 6, 2021, Tesla formally notified people who had pre-ordered the Long Range RWD that their chosen configuration is no longer available.<ref name=":3">{{Cite web|last=Mihalascu|first=Dan|date=December 6, 2021|title=It's Official, Tesla Model Y Long Range RWD Not Going To Happen
|url=https://insideevs.com/news/552675/tesla-modely-longrangerwd-officially-shelved/|website=Inside EVs|access-date=December 6, 2021|language=en-US}}</ref>

==History==
{{cleanup rewrite|section=yes|date=June 2021}}
[[File:Tesla 3 + Y.jpg|thumb|right|300px|Tesla Model 3 (left) and Tesla Model Y (right) side by side]]
In 2013, Tesla Motors filed to trademark "Model Y".<ref name=TT-2016-04-11>{{Cite news |url= http://www.techtimes.com/articles/148939/20160411/if-ford-did-not-block-trademark-for-model-e-tesla-would-have-completed-a-word-after-model-s-model-x.htm |title= If Ford Did Not Block Trademark For Model E, Tesla Would Have Completed A Word After Model S, Model X |date= April 11, 2016 |author= Santiago Tiongco |work= Tech Times |access-date= March 15, 2019 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20190330205509/https://www.techtimes.com/articles/148939/20160411/if-ford-did-not-block-trademark-for-model-e-tesla-would-have-completed-a-word-after-model-s-model-x.htm |archive-date= March 30, 2019 |url-status= live }}</ref>

In 2015, [[Elon Musk]] teased a Model 3-based Model Y with [[Gull-wing door|falcon-wing doors]].<ref name=ars-2015-10-07>{{cite news |url= https://arstechnica.com/cars/2015/10/tesla-model-y-with-falcon-wing-doors-hinted-at-by-elon-musk/ |title= Elon Musk hints at Tesla Model Y with falcon-wing doors |author= Sebastian Anthony |date= October 7, 2015 |work= [[art tech]] |access-date= March 15, 2019 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20190330193150/https://arstechnica.com/cars/2015/10/tesla-model-y-with-falcon-wing-doors-hinted-at-by-elon-musk/ |archive-date= March 30, 2019 |url-status= live }}</ref>

In 2017, the Model Y's silhouette was teased to Tesla shareholders at the annual general meeting in June.<ref name=Guardian-2017-06-07>{{cite news |url= https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2017/jun/07/tesla-teases-new-model-y-car-cheaper-model-3-production-elon-musk |title= Tesla teases new Model Y car as cheaper Model 3 nears production |author= Samuel Gibbs |date= June 7, 2020 |newspaper= [[The Guardian]] |access-date= March 15, 2019 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20190330181733/https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2017/jun/07/tesla-teases-new-model-y-car-cheaper-model-3-production-elon-musk |archive-date= March 30, 2019 |url-status= live }}</ref> Elon Musk also announced that the Model Y would be produced in a new factory, as it was not likely that the [[Tesla Factory|Fremont plant]] would have room to accommodate another production line.<ref name=WSJ-2017-06-06>{{cite news |url= https://www.wsj.com/articles/tesla-ceo-elon-musk-signals-new-factory-for-model-y-suv-1496797117 |title= Tesla CEO Elon Musk Signals New Factory for Model Y SUV |author= Tim Higgins |date= June 6, 2017 |newspaper= The Wall Street Journal |access-date= March 15, 2019 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20190316150723/https://www.wsj.com/articles/tesla-ceo-elon-musk-signals-new-factory-for-model-y-suv-1496797117 |archive-date= March 16, 2019 |url-status= live }}</ref>

In June 2018, a new silhouette was revealed by CEO Musk. With the new image, it was stated that the Model Y would be formally announced in March 2019.<ref name=Fortune-2018-06-06>{{cite news |url= http://fortune.com/2018/06/06/elon-musk-tesla-model-y-image/ |title= Elon Musk Shares a New Image of the Tesla Model Y |author= LISA MARIE SEGARRA |date= June 6, 2018 |work= [[Fortune (magazine)|Fortune]] |access-date= March 15, 2019 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20190330193202/http://fortune.com/2018/06/06/elon-musk-tesla-model-y-image/ |archive-date= March 30, 2019 |url-status= live }}</ref> The Model Y announcement had been planned for 2018; however, production problems with the Model 3 resulted in it being pushed to 2019.<ref name=Electrek-2018-10-22>{{cite web |url= https://electrek.co/2018/10/22/tesla-model-y/ |title= Tesla Model Y: what to expect? |author= Fred Lambert |date= October 22, 2018 |publisher= Electrek |access-date= March 15, 2019 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20190330205319/https://electrek.co/2018/10/22/tesla-model-y/ |archive-date= March 30, 2019 |url-status= live }}</ref> In October 2018, Elon Musk revealed that he has approved the finalized design for the first production version of the Model Y, however production would not start until 2020.<ref name=Verge-2018-10-24>{{cite news |url= https://www.theverge.com/2018/10/24/18020936/teslas-model-y-crossover-prototype-production |title= Tesla's Model Y crossover is ready for production, Elon Musk says |author= Sean O'Kane |date= October 24, 2018 |work= [[The Verge]] |access-date= March 15, 2019 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20190330205340/https://www.theverge.com/2018/10/24/18020936/teslas-model-y-crossover-prototype-production |archive-date= March 30, 2019 |url-status= live }}</ref> On March 3, 2019, Elon Musk published multiple tweets, announcing the unveiling event and confirming some specifications.<ref name=Twitter-1102332778492772352>{{Cite tweet |author=Elon Musk |user=elonmusk |number=1102332778492772352 |title=Model Y unveil event on March 14 at LA Design Studio |date=March 3, 2019|website=@elonmusk|language=en|access-date=March 4, 2019|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20190303235845/https://twitter.com/elonmusk/status/1102332778492772352 |archive-date=March 3, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Musk confirmed the vehicle would use standard doors, as opposed to the falcon-wing doors used on the Model X.<ref name=Twitter-1102340302663180288>{{Cite tweet |author=Elon Musk |user=elonmusk |number=1102340302663180288 |title=Normal |date=March 3, 2019 |language=en |access-date=March 4, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190407170743/https://twitter.com/elonmusk/status/1102340302663180288 |archive-date=April 7, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref>

On March 14, 2019, Elon Musk premiered the Tesla Model Y at an event at Tesla's design studio in Hawthorne, CA, where specifications were announced and the vehicle was shown. Test drives of multiple Model Y vehicles were also offered to attendees after the presentation.<ref name="electrek-2019-03-14" /><ref name=Teslarati-2021>{{Cite web|url=https://www.teslarati.com/tesla-model-y-test-ride-video/ |title=Tesla Model Y test ride: first impressions of Tesla's latest 7-seat SUV (picture)|last=Alvarez|first=Simon |date=March 15, 2019|website=TESLARATI|language=en-US|access-date=March 15, 2019|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20190330205313/https://www.teslarati.com/tesla-model-y-test-ride-video/ |archive-date=March 30, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Due to its larger size, the Y consumes more energy than the 3, and thus has shorter range. The Fremont factory was changed to accommodate production of the Y.<ref name="ct2019-08-21">{{cite web |last1=Field |first1=Kyle |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20190821223314/https://cleantechnica.com/2019/06/08/streamlining-manufacturing-of-the-tesla-model-3-for-the-model-y/ |archive-date=August 21, 2019 |url-status=live |title=Streamlining Manufacturing of the Tesla Model 3 For The Model Y |url=https://cleantechnica.com/2019/06/08/streamlining-manufacturing-of-the-tesla-model-3-for-the-model-y/ |website=CleanTechnica |date=June 8, 2019 |quote=the Model Y is notably larger than the Model 3 and has a larger frontal surface area as a result. Combined with its 8–10% heavier build, that will result in a lower efficiency than the 3}}</ref>

In November 2019, Tesla announced that the Tesla Model Y would be the first vehicle to be assembled at the first European Gigafactory, [[Giga Berlin]].<ref name=electrek20191112>{{cite news |url=http://electrek.co/2019/11/12/tesla-gigafactory-4-berlin-germany/ |title=Elon Musk: Tesla is going to build Giga Berlin |work=Electrek |date=November 12, 2019 |access-date=November 13, 2019 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20191112210609/https://electrek.co/2019/11/12/tesla-gigafactory-4-berlin-germany/ |archive-date=November 12, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite AV media |date=November 12, 2019 |title=Die Verleihung des Goldenen Lenkrads 2019: Das sind die besten Autos des Jahres! |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=O8iEEVbhkR0&t=2490s |publisher=AUTO BILD }}</ref>

On January 29, 2020, Tesla reported in its Q4 2019 earnings report that Model Y production had already started in the Fremont factory, that one can now place an order for their premium versions with all-wheel drive, and that delivery of Model Y would begin in Q1 2020.<ref name=2019-q4-ir>{{Cite web|url=https://ir.tesla.com/static-files/b3cf7f5e-546a-4a65-9888-c928b914b529 |title=Q4 and FY2019 Update|website=Tesla |access-date=February 27, 2020}}</ref>

On March 13, 2020, Tesla made their first deliveries of the Model Y, along with publishing its owner's manual.<ref name=":0">{{cite news|url= https://electrek.co/2020/03/13/tesla-model-y-specs-we-finally-know-how-big-it-is/ |website= electrek.co |title= Tesla Model Y specs: we finally know how big it is |first= Jameson |last= Dow |date= March 13, 2020 |access-date= March 14, 2020}}</ref>

On August 13, 2020, it was reported that Tesla Fremont would soon activate the world's largest unibody casting machine for Model Y production, switching to casting the rear body in a single piece.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.tesmanian.com/blogs/tesmanian-blog/tesla-model-y-from-fremont-will-soon-use-the-biggest-casting-machine-for-mass-production|title=Tesla Fremont to Soon Activate World's Largest Unibody Casting Machine in Mass Model Y Production|website=TESMANIAN}}</ref> Elon Musk told an interviewer that the Berlin-made Model Y is "not just a copy of the Model Y. It's actually a radical redesign of the core technology of building a car."<ref name="auto1">{{Cite web |title=Elon Musk shares details on Tesla Model Y redesign, battery cell production in Giga Berlin |url=https://www.teslarati.com/tesla-model-y-redesign-giga-berlin-battery-cell-production-details-elon-musk-interview-video/}}</ref> For the made-in-Berlin Model Y, rear and front portions of the frame will be a single-cast design. Injecting molten aluminum into a cast and having robots pull out the molded metal allows Tesla to combine several manufacturing steps.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://europe.autonews.com/automakers/tesla-bets-aluminum-casting-german-plant|title=Tesla bets on aluminum casting for German plant|date=September 8, 2020|website=Automotive News Europe}}</ref> This manufacturing process is expected to result in significant savings, including lower tool investments, reduced production time, lower number of robots, and a smaller production area.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fahrzeug-karosserie.de/karosserie-aus-einem-guss-eine-schoene-und-lohnenswerte-aufgabe-a-957640/|title=Karosserie aus einem Guss: "Eine schöne und lohnenswerte Aufgabe"|website=fahrzeug-karosserie.de}}</ref>

On June 5, 2020, Tesla launched the Model Y Online design studio for the Chinese market, allowing customers in China to place orders for the upcoming made-in-China Model Y.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://insideevs.com/news/427178/tesla-model-y-online-design-studio-china/|title=Tesla Launches Model Y Online Design Studio For Chinese Market|website=InsideEVs}}</ref> First delivery of the model was made on January 18, 2021.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Moss|first=Trefor|date=January 18, 2021|title=Tesla Starts Delivering China-Made Model Y Crossover|language=en-US|work=The Wall Street Journal|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/tesla-starts-delivering-china-made-model-y-crossover-11610966805|access-date=January 19, 2021|issn=0099-9660}}</ref>

Initial production of the made-in-China Model Y began in mid-December 2020 with 250,000 Model Y expected to be produced in 2021 in China alone.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.teslarati.com/tesla-model-y-production-begins-giga-shangha-video/|title=Tesla Model Y initial production begins in Gigafactory Shanghai|website=Teslarati}}</ref>

On September 8, 2020, Volkswagen Group Chairperson of the Board of Management, [[Herbert Diess]], wrote about the Model Y: "This car is for us in many aspects (not in all!) a reference: user experience, updatability, driving features, performance of the top of the range models, charging network, range. Big advantage: Model Y was/is thought through as an electric car – as is the [[Volkswagen ID.3|ID.3]]. Many of our competitors still using their ICE platforms. The result: They aren’t getting the best EVs."<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.teslarati.com/tesla-model-y-review-vw-herbert-diess-insights/|title=Tesla Model Y leaves strong impression on VW's Herbert Diess after test drive}}</ref>

On October 7, 2020, Musk tweeted that Giga Berlin Model Y would get single-piece rear and front frame cast, [[Structural battery|structural battery pack]], and new 4680 cells.<ref>{{Cite tweet |author=Elon Musk |user=elonmusk |title=Giga Berlin Model Y will get single-piece rear and front frame cast |number=1313854912212750346 |access-date=October 7, 2020 |date=October 7, 2020 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|title=Tesla Model Y from Giga Berlin will utilize 4680 cells and structural battery pack|url=https://www.teslarati.com/tesla-model-y-giga-berlin-4680-cells-structural-battery-pack-confirmed-elon-musk|website=Teslarati|date=October 7, 2020}}</ref>

On January 1, 2021, Tesla started selling the Model Y in China, and it sold out its planned production (an unknown quantity) for Q1 2021 within 6 days.<ref>{{Cite web|last=Insights|first=Benzinga EV|date=January 6, 2021|title=Tesla Sells Out Of Q1 Supply Of Model Y In China Just Days After Opening Order Page: Report|url=https://www.benzinga.com/tech/21/01/19042173/tesla-sells-out-of-q1-supply-of-model-y-in-china-just-days-after-opening-order-page-report|access-date=January 9, 2021|website=Benzinga|language=en}}</ref>

On January 7, 2021, Tesla released the Standard Range Rear Wheel Drive Model Y as well as the optional 7-seat, third-row seating configuration.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Tesla launches Model Y with Standard Range RWD and 7-seat third-row option|url=https://electrek.co/2021/01/07/tesla-model-y-standard-range-rwd-third-row-option|website=Electrek|date=January 8, 2021}}</ref>

On July 25, 2021, CEO Elon Musk revealed that Tesla was planning to release an updated design for the Model Y by the end of 2021. In addition, Tesla planned to implement their new structural battery pack to improve range. These new cars would be manufactured by the two new Tesla production facilities in Austin, Texas and Berlin, Germany. If Tesla was not able to roll out the new 4680 battery cells by the end of 2021, they would use the standard battery cells until the 4680's are ready.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.inverse.com/innovation/tesla-model-y-suv-redesign|title = Tesla Model y: Elon Musk teases 'new design' to reach even more buyers}}</ref>[[File:Tesla Model 3 Screen Dec 2020.jpg|thumb|Center-mounted {{convert|15.4|in|cm|adj=on}} [[Liquid-crystal display|LCD]] [[touchscreen]],<ref name=dash>{{cite web|url=https://www.theverge.com/2017/7/31/16067728/tesla-model-3-apple-iphone-comparison|title=Tesla's Model 3 and Apple's iPhone have a few things in common|date=July 31, 2017|access-date=August 1, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170731170204/https://www.theverge.com/2017/7/31/16067728/tesla-model-3-apple-iphone-comparison|archive-date=July 31, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> sporting the new UI design from Tesla's December 2020 "Holiday Update"<ref>{{Cite web|last=Merano|first=Maria|date=December 25, 2020|title=Tesla rolls out 2020 Holiday Update: New Driving Visualizations, Supercharger Display Improvements and more (Release Notes)|url=https://www.teslarati.com/tesla-holiday-update-2020-release-notes/|access-date=April 30, 2021}}</ref>]]
