=== Heat pump ===
The Model Y is Tesla's first car to use a [[heat pump]] instead of electric resistance for interior cabin heating.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://electrek.co/2020/03/23/tesla-model-y-heat-pump-elon-musk-best-engineering/|title=Elon Musk: Tesla Model Y heat pump is some of the best engineering I've seen in a while|last=Lambert|first=Fred|date=March 24, 2020|website=Electrek |access-date=March 25, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.currentautomotive.com/model-y-is-the-first-tesla-with-a-heat-pump-heres-why-thats-a-big-deal/|title=Model Y is the first Tesla with a heat pump. Here's why that's a big deal.|last=Erwin|first=Blane|date=March 26, 2020|website=Current Automotive |access-date=April 6, 2020}}</ref> Some electric vehicles from other manufacturers, including the [[Nissan Leaf]], [[Renault Zoe]], [[BMW i3|BMW i3 EV]], [[Jaguar I-Pace]], [[Audi e-tron (2018)|Audi e-tron]], and [[Kia Niro]], had already implemented heat pumps.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.greencarreports.com/news/1124387_can-heat-pumps-solve-cold-weather-range-loss-for-evs|title=Can heat pumps solve cold-weather range loss for EVs?|website=Green Car Reports |access-date=March 25, 2020}}</ref> In cold weather, the Model Y heat pump can be up to 300% more efficient than other Tesla cars' use of electric resistance heating.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.tesmanian.com/blogs/tesmanian-blog/tesla-model-y-heat-pump-range|title=Tesla Model Y Heat Pump: Deep Dive and Closer Look |website=Tesmanian |access-date=March 25, 2020}}</ref> Because of this, the Model Y should be more energy efficient than other Tesla cars in cold weather.<ref name="auto">{{Cite web|url=https://thedriven.io/2020/03/18/model-y-has-heat-pump-to-solve-issue-of-range-in-cold-weather/|title=Model Y has heat pump to solve issue of range in cold weather|last=Schmidt|first=Bridie|date=March 18, 2020|website=The Driven |access-date=March 25, 2020}}</ref> Electric cars can lose 40% or more of their range in cold weather (at ambient temperatures below {{Convert|20|F|C}}) when heating the interior cabin.<ref name="auto" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.marketwatch.com/story/cold-weather-saps-electric-car-batteries-2019-02-07|title=Tesla and other electric car batteries lose 40% of their range in extremely cold weather: AAA|agency=Associated Press|website=MarketWatch |access-date=March 25, 2020}}</ref>

During his teardown of the Model Y,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://munrolive.com/|title=Model Y & Cybertruck Reviews|website=Munrolive}}</ref> auto analyst [[Sandy Munro]] found a component that has been referred to as the "octovalve", which appears to be the next iteration of the superbottle component used in the Model 3.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.tesmanian.com/blogs/tesmanian-blog/tesla-model-y-easter-egg-octovalve-sandy-munro-teardown |title=Sandy Munro Finds Fun 'Octovalve' Tesla Model Y Easter Egg During Teardown |date=April 4, 2020 |access-date=April 18, 2020 |work=Tesmanian |last=Deveza |first=Ma. Claribelle}}</ref> Musk has said that the new heat pump system/octovalve is one of the two most significant changes in the Model Y over the Model 3, the other being the new rear underbody [[casting]].<ref name="musk20200414">{{cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=pih4kU6yvz8 |title=Elon Musk discusses Model Y |work=Third Row Tesla |date=April 14, 2020 |time=1:25–7:30 |access-date=April 20, 2020}}</ref> The octovalve supports the Model Y heat pump as part of the car's thermal management system.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.teslarati.com/tesla-model-y-octovalve-easter-egg-teardown/ |title=Tesla proudly hides 'Octovalve' insignia in Model Y, hints at next-gen thermal system |date=April 5, 2020 |access-date=April 18, 2020 |work=Teslarati |last=Alvarez |first=Simon}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://insideevs.com/news/408232/tesla-octovalve-sandy-munro-unshot-video/ |title=Tesla Octovalve Is The Video Sandy Munro Has Not Captured Yet |date=April 6, 2020 |access-date=April 18, 2020 |work=InsideEVs |last=Ruffo |first=Gustavo Henrique}}</ref>

=== Radar ===
Vehicles produced since May 2021 lack [[radar]] for [[adaptive cruise control]].<ref name=c&d20220228>[https://www.caranddriver.com/news/a39250157/tesla-no-radar-sensor-model-s-model-x/ Tesla Stops Putting Radar Sensors in New Model S and Model X EVs], February 28, 2022. Retrieved July 3, 2022</ref> In February 2022, the [[National Highway Traffic Safety Administration]] opened an investigation over phantom braking in these new vehicles.<ref>[https://www.bbc.com/news/technology-60432351 Tesla investigated over 'phantom braking' problem]</ref>

==Production==
{{expand section|article is oddly missing nearly all information on actual production since Model Y production began in 2020|date=July 2022}}
Tesla originally announced plans at the unveil to assemble the Model Y at [[Giga Nevada]] (in Sparks, Nevada), along with the battery and drivetrain for the vehicles, unlike the Model 3, where drivetrains and batteries are assembled at Giga Nevada, with final assembly completed at the [[Tesla Factory]] in [[Fremont, California]]. Two months later, in May 2019, Tesla said that they instead planned to shuffle production lines at the Tesla Fremont Factory to make space for Model Y production.<ref name=CNBC-2019-05-29>{{cite web|last1=Kolodny|first1=Lora|title=Tesla is rejiggering its Fremont factory to build the Model Y SUV and a Model S refresh|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2019/05/29/tesla-fremont-factory-prepping-for-model-y-production-model-s-refresh.html|publisher=CNBC|date=May 29, 2019|access-date=June 3, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190602063953/https://www.cnbc.com/2019/05/29/tesla-fremont-factory-prepping-for-model-y-production-model-s-refresh.html|archive-date=June 2, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Later, Model Y would also be assembled at [[Giga Shanghai]]{{when|date=July 2022}} in China<ref name=CarAndDriver-2019-03-15>{{cite magazine|last1=Capparella|first1=Joey|title=The Tesla Model Y Is the All-Electric Brand's Entry into the Compact-Crossover Fray|url=https://www.caranddriver.com/news/a26828716/tesla-model-y-photos-info/|magazine=[[Car and Driver]]|date=March 15, 2019|access-date=March 14, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190403044043/https://www.caranddriver.com/news/a26828716/tesla-model-y-photos-info/|archive-date=April 3, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> and [[Giga Berlin]] in Germany.<ref name="electrek20191112" />

United States deliveries started in March 2020 for the Long Range AWD version and the Performance version. Later in 2020, Tesla began shipping cars to the Canadian and Mexican markets.

In November 2020, Tesla signed an agreement with [[LG Chem]] to supply battery cells for Model Y production in China.<ref name="LG Chem">{{cite web |last1=Merano |first1=Maria |title=Tesla China signs contract with LG Chem for Model Y production |url=https://www.teslarati.com/tesla-china-signs-contract-with-lg-chem-for-model-y-production/ |website=TESLARATI |access-date=November 23, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201123203347/https://www.teslarati.com/tesla-china-signs-contract-with-lg-chem-for-model-y-production/ |archive-date=November 23, 2020 |date=November 23, 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref>

